agic and ironic bent of the Book of Job, Job as mourner, and the Joban body in pain, and ends with a consideration of Joban works by notable writers - from Melville and Kafka, through Joseph Roth, Zach, Levin, and Philip Roth.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSocial sciences. 4aBibel. 4aHermeneutik. 4aReligion. 4aÄsthetik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aBible.  aHermeneutics.  aReligion.1 aAlter, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatnitzky, Leora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatnitzky, Leora, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalbertal, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan-Rokem, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschfeld, Ariel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiska, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeshel, Naphtali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPardes, Ilana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPardes, Ilana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRaz, Yosefa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRokem, Freddie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is par